I remember 19... I think we were listening to the jungle drums in South Africa as they told us about the Monguls that invaded China several planting seasons earlier.<br>
<br>
Anyway, first and foremost, you seem like you have a good head on your shoulders (to coin another pharse) and you will do just fine. There are, however, a few things you say that I remember saying myself, only to find out that this happens way more in Halmark Cards and Julia Roberts movies than in real life (sorry Roberts fans.. I'm jaded). <br>
First of all, the idea of a lover that will hit you like a mystical lightening bolt from the sky is a nice fantasy, but hardly EVER true. Yes, it does happen sometimes, and I have seen ONE couple that had that take place. ONE. I have known THOUSANDS, and it only happened to ONE. The truth is that you will likely find someone that is your friend, and later becomes your lover. Perhaps one of the strongest relationships I have ever seen was a couple that got together and were friends for years before their first kiss. <br>
This isn't like shopping for a mini-van. You don't make sure the tires are inflated properly and the muffler doesn't rattle. If you are talking about a lasting relationship, you are talking about something that will continue to grow and develop with you as long as the two of you are together. Sometimes you will find out that you are better friends than lovers, it's just the way it is. To wit, my very best friend right now is a former lover. It happens.<br>
Now, if what you say about your drug/alcohol use is true, bravo! If possible, I would shake your hand and congratulate you for making a very hard and extremely wise decision. At your age especially, you need to avoid making choices that will make your life even more difficult than it already is. Yes, I started binge drinking when I was 18 (that was the legal age then) and quit when I was 25, but I have also been told time and again how rare that is. What is more, I made MORE stupid choices becasue of that action than nearly any other I have made over the course fo my life. Luckily, none of these led to an unwanted pregnency or incurable STD. Don't put yourself in that position if you can avoid it. You have made some wise decisions, I salute you for them. Keep it up.<br>
Finally (and this could be more cultural than anything else), you seem very concerned about the outside and not to worried about the person. Whether or not she is a virgin will not made a whole lot of differance if your personalities are compatible. Her height and physical appearance is a VERY temporary atribute, as is yours. If you want to develop a lasting relationship, it has to go beneath the surface. Discover who you are, find out what you like, learn about that which intereasts you, then talk to people about those things. If there is any path to the &quot;star crossed lovers&quot; I would say this is it. I have seen people take up a habbit to &quot;meet chicks&quot; only to find out that they don't like the activity and like the &quot;chicks&quot; even less. Moral of the story, don't take up Nude Square Dancing to meet women, do it because you want to square dance in the nude. Chances are there will be other women there that also enjoy nude Square Dancing, and you are going to be infinately more likely to get along with them because you share an intereast.<br>
And finally, the magical element. The one factor that will make any relationship fail (if it is missing) is comunication. BASICALLY, tell so-and-so to tell such-and-such will never last. If the two of you can't talk to eachother, how can you ever expect to live together in a meaningful and fulfilling exchange? If you are looking for a lasting relationship, you need to offer more than a charming smile and trendy phrases (bling-bling... WTF does that mean?). If it is going to work, you need to be able to share yourself with her, and let her share herself with you... AND be secure in doing that. Kissing, petting, sexual games and parties ... it comes in time (pardon the pun) if that's what you want. The physical aspect is VERY easy, but the emotional is WAY harder. What is more, you can go through the motions and get the physical easy enough. You can only fake the emotional for a short time, and once the facade starts to fail, there is NO saving it. <br>
<br>
Now, I am sure there are those out there that will say I am full of shit, to which I say ... fine.  I have comforted enough of the girls who's hearts were broken by caloussed SOBs like you to know what I am talking about. (bling bling?).  I see in Xanthus a person that wants to do the right thing, just isn't really too sure what that thing is.  To him I say Keep doing what you are doing now.  You are going in the right direction, just have a little more patience.  If you want a course of action, then I offer you this advice: <br>
As the saying goes, &quot;Know thyself.  No single aspect of thine is more important.&quot; <p><!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
